VALUES
(42, 4, 23, 43, 2, 3, 4, NULL, 'Healing and Response to Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus responding to needs. In both passages, there is an expectation of action from Jesus, whether to heal or provide wine, reflecting a common motif of divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 23, 45, 2, 21, 22, 'Physician, heal thyself', 'Self-Reflection in Teaching', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-examination in teaching and healing. Both passages emphasize the expectation that one should practice what they preach or teach, questioning the integrity of actions versus words.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 24, 40, 13, 57, 57, 'No prophet is accepted in his own country', 'Prophet''s Rejection Theme', 'Both passages emphasize that a prophet is not honored in his own country. This connection highlights the common theme of rejection faced by prophets among their own people.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 24, 43, 4, 44, 44, NULL, 'Prophet''s Lack of Honor', 'Both passages emphasize that a prophet is not accepted in his own country. This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by prophets in familiar settings.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 24, 41, 6, 4, 5, 'No prophet is accepted in his own country', 'Rejection of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of honor for prophets in their own country. This connection highlights the challenges Jesus faced among his own people, as noted in both verses.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 24, 44, 22, 3, 3, 'No prophet is accepted in his own country', 'Rejection of Prophets Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of a prophet''s rejection in their own community. In Luke, Jesus states that ''No prophet is accepted in his own country,'' while in Acts, Paul reflects on his Jewish identity and upbringing, suggesting a similar experience of rejection among his own people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 24, 44, 22, 18, 22, 'No prophet is accepted in his own country', 'Rejection of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of prophets in their own communities. Luke 4:24 states that no prophet is accepted in his own country, while Acts 22:18 highlights the refusal of the people in Jerusalem to receive Paul''s testimony.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 11, 17, 1, 1, 'great famine was throughout all the land', 'Connection of Famine and Elijah', 'Both passages emphasize a period of famine caused by Elijah''s prophecy. Luke references the famine during Elijah''s time, highlighting the significance of his role in Israel''s history.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 59, 5, 17, 17, 'three years and six months', 'Connection of Elijah''s Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the period of ''three years and six months'' during which Elijah prayed for drought. This connection highlights Elijah''s role as a prophet and the significance of his prayer in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 23, 55, 8, 8, 'great famine was throughout all the land', 'Divine Perspective on Human Suffering', 'This connection highlights the contrast between human understanding and divine wisdom. In times of famine, as noted in Luke, God''s ways and thoughts remain beyond human comprehension, as expressed in Isaiah.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 40, 20, 15, 15, NULL, 'Divine Sovereignty and Goodness', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s authority over provision and goodness. In both passages, the emphasis is on God''s right to act according to His will, whether in times of famine or in His generosity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 11, 18, 1, 2, 'great famine was throughout all the land', 'Connection of Famine and Elijah', 'Both passages emphasize a famine during Elijah''s time. Luke references the famine in Israel, while 1 Kings describes the same famine and its duration. This connection highlights the significance of Elijah''s prophetic ministry amid hardship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 41, 7, 26, 29, NULL, 'Connection of Faith and Inclusion', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith transcending ethnic boundaries. In both passages, the focus is on God''s provision and mercy, as seen in the widow''s story during famine and the Syrophenician woman''s plea for her daughter.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 25, 42, 10, 21, 21, 'many widows were in Israel', 'Revelation to the Humble', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine revelation to those considered lowly or humble. In Luke 4:25, the mention of widows highlights God''s care for the marginalized, while Luke 10:21 speaks of revealing truths to ''babes,'' suggesting a similar divine preference.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 26, 11, 17, 9, 24, 'unto a woman that was a widow', 'Connection of Widow and Provision', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a widow in a time of need, showcasing God''s provision through Elijah. The widow''s faith and subsequent miracles highlight her significance in both narratives.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 26, 40, 11, 21, 21, 'Sidon', 'Connection of Sidon References', 'Both passages emphasize Sidon, linking the widow''s story in Luke to the condemnation of Chorazin and Bethsaida in Matthew. This connection highlights the significance of Sidon as a place of repentance contrasted with the unrepentant cities of Israel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 26, 31, 1, 20, 20, 'unto Sarepta, a city of Sidon', 'Connection of Locations and Themes', 'This connection highlights the mention of Zarephath in both passages, linking the widow of Sarepta in Luke to the broader theme of Israel''s restoration and possession of lands. Both verses emphasize the significance of these locations in the context of God''s provision and promise.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 12, 5, 1, 27, 'none of them was cleansed, saving Naaman the Syrian', 'Connection of Naaman''s Cleansing', 'Both passages emphasize Naaman''s healing from leprosy, highlighting the miraculous act performed by the prophet Elisha. Luke references this event to illustrate God''s power to heal even outside Israel, as Naaman was a Syrian.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 43, 17, 12, 12, NULL, 'Cleansing and Preservation Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of preservation in both passages. In Luke, Naaman is the only leper cleansed, while in John, Jesus keeps all but one disciple safe.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 11, 19, 19, 21, 'none of them was cleansed, saving Naaman', 'Connection through Elisha and Naaman', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Elisha in miraculous healings, specifically highlighting Naaman''s cleansing from leprosy. This connection underscores Elisha''s prophetic authority and the significance of his actions in relation to outsiders like Naaman.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 40, 12, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Unlawful Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of actions that defy societal norms or laws. Both passages emphasize instances where individuals, Naaman and David, act outside the expected boundaries, showcasing God''s mercy and provision.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 18, 21, 22, 22, 'none of them was cleansed', 'Judgment and Cleansing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and the selective nature of God''s mercy. In both passages, the emphasis is on God''s authority to judge and cleanse, as seen in the mention of Naaman''s healing amidst many lepers and God''s judgment of the high.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 18, 33, 13, 13, NULL, 'Divine Sovereignty and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize God''s control over healing and suffering. In Luke, the cleansing of Naaman highlights God''s selective mercy, while Job reflects on God''s inscrutable ways, suggesting that His decisions are beyond human understanding.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 27, 27, 4, 35, 35, NULL, 'Divine Authority and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over healing and human condition. Both passages emphasize that God acts according to His will, as seen in the cleansing of Naaman and the sovereignty expressed in Daniel.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 28, 14, 24, 20, 21, 'were filled with wrath', 'Rejection of Prophetic Messages', 'Both passages emphasize the wrath of the people towards those delivering God''s message. In Luke, the synagogue''s anger parallels the violent response to Zechariah''s prophetic warning in Chronicles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 28, 24, 37, 15, 16, 'filled with wrath', 'Wrath Against Prophetic Voices', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of wrath directed at prophets. In Luke, the synagogue''s anger mirrors the princes'' wrath against Jeremiah, highlighting a consistent response to prophetic messages.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 28, 24, 38, 6, 6, NULL, 'Rejection and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by prophets. In both passages, the response to the prophet''s message leads to severe consequences, illustrating the hostility towards divine messengers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 28, 42, 6, 11, 11, 'filled with wrath', 'Emotional Responses to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize intense emotional reactions to Jesus'' words. In Luke 4:28, the synagogue''s wrath parallels the madness described in Luke 6:11, highlighting a growing hostility towards Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 28, 42, 11, 53, 54, 'filled with wrath', 'Response to Hostility', 'Both passages emphasize the intense opposition Jesus faced. In Luke 4:28, the synagogue''s wrath parallels the scribes and Pharisees'' vehement urging in Luke 11:53-54, highlighting a consistent theme of hostility towards Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 28, 44, 5, 33, 33, 'filled with wrath', 'Response to Provocation', 'Both passages emphasize a strong emotional reaction to the message delivered. In Luke, the synagogue''s wrath parallels the anger in Acts, where the listeners are cut to the heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
